<!-- wp:heading {"level":1} -->
<h1>Understanding Community-Acquired Pneumonia</h1>
<!-- /wp:heading -->

<!-- wp:list -->
<ul><li><a href="https://www.healthline.com/health/pneumonia/pneumonia-stages#causes">Causes</a></li><li><a href="https://www.healthline.com/health/pneumonia/pneumonia-stages#risk-factors">Risk factors</a></li><li><a href="https://www.healthline.com/health/pneumonia/pneumonia-stages#symptoms">Symptoms</a></li><li><a href="https://www.healthline.com/health/pneumonia/pneumonia-stages#diagnosis">Diagnosis</a></li><li><a href="https://www.healthline.com/health/pneumonia/pneumonia-stages#treatment">Treatment</a></li><li><a href="https://www.healthline.com/health/pneumonia/pneumonia-stages#complications">Complications</a></li><li><a href="https://www.healthline.com/health/pneumonia/pneumonia-stages#outlook">Outlook</a></li><li><a href="https://www.healthline.com/health/pneumonia/pneumonia-stages#prevention">Prevention</a></li><li><a href="https://www.healthline.com/health/pneumonia/pneumonia-stages#takeaway">Takeaway</a></li></ul>
<!-- /wp:list -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>Pneumonia is an infection in one or both lungs. Bacteria and viruses typically cause pneumonia. Fungi can also cause some types of pneumonia.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>Pneumonia affects&nbsp;<a href="https://www.cdc.gov/dotw/pneumonia/index.html" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">millions of peopleTrusted Source</a>&nbsp;around the world each year. In the United States, about&nbsp;<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK430749/" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">25 of every 10,000 peopleTrusted Source</a>&nbsp;get pneumonia each year. That rate gets higher as age increases.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>Some people develop a serious case of&nbsp;<a href="https://www.healthline.com/health/pneumonia">pneumonia</a>&nbsp;while in the hospital. But it’s more common to develop pneumonia outside a hospital setting. When this happens, doctors refer to it as community-acquired pneumonia (CAP).</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>CAP is the&nbsp;<a href="https://journal.chestnet.org/article/S0012-3692(17)30916-9/fulltext" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">most common</a>&nbsp;type of pneumonia people experience. Although it’s not usually as serious as hospital-acquired pneumonia (HAP), it can still have serious complications.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>This article will look at CAP, how it compares with other types of pneumonia, and what you can do to protect yourself.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:heading {"level":3} -->
<h3>Types of pneumonia</h3>
<!-- /wp:heading -->

<!-- wp:list -->
<ul><li><strong>Community-acquired pneumonia (CAP):</strong>&nbsp;CAP refers to pneumonia you develop outside a hospital setting.</li><li><strong>Hospital-acquired pneumonia (HAP):</strong>&nbsp;Also called&nbsp;<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK535441/" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">nosocomial pneumoniaTrusted Source</a>, HAP occurs if you fall ill with pneumonia 48 hours or more after your admission to the hospital. HAP is usually more serious than CAP because it can involve bacteria that are&nbsp;<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK525768/" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">resistant to antibioticsTrusted Source</a>.</li><li><strong>Ventilator-associated pneumonia (VAP):</strong>&nbsp;A subgroup of people with HAP may develop VAP. It occurs in hospital patients who are receiving&nbsp;<a href="https://www.healthline.com/health/ventilator">mechanical ventilation</a>&nbsp;for respiratory failure.</li></ul>
<!-- /wp:list -->

<!-- wp:heading -->
<h2><a>What causes community-acquired pneumonia?</a></h2>
<!-- /wp:heading -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>Pneumonia has many causes.&nbsp;<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC7149822/" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">Research from 2017Trusted Source</a>&nbsp;references 26 common causes of CAP, mainly bacteria and viruses.&nbsp;<a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/32629490/" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">Some fungiTrusted Source</a>&nbsp;can also cause CAP.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>The&nbsp;<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK430749/" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">most commonTrusted Source</a>&nbsp;causes of CAP in the United States are:</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:list -->
<ul><li>human rhinovirus (<a href="https://www.healthline.com/health/cold-flu/cold">common cold</a>)</li><li>influenza virus (<a href="https://www.healthline.com/health/cold-flu/flu">flu</a>)</li><li><em>Streptococcus pneumoniae</em></li></ul>
<!-- /wp:list -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>Other common causes include:</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:list -->
<ul><li>the coronavirus SARS-CoV-2 (<a href="https://www.healthline.com/health/coronavirus-covid-19">COVID-19</a>)</li><li><em>Haemophilus influenzae</em></li><li><em>Legionella</em>&nbsp;bacteria</li><li><em>Mycoplasma pneumonia</em></li><li>hard-to-detect bacteria, such as&nbsp;<em>Chlamydia pneumoniae</em></li></ul>
<!-- /wp:list -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>So, how do humans come in contact with these germs?</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>Some of them, like&nbsp;<em>Streptococcus pneumoniae</em>, already live in your nose, sinuses, or mouth. They can eventually spread to your lungs, where they cause disease. It’s unclear why they invade the lungs.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>You might also breathe in these germs if they are in the air around you. Certain activities or environments may increase your risk of coming in contact with them.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:heading -->
<h2><a>Who is at risk of community-acquired pneumonia?</a></h2>
<!-- /wp:heading -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>CAP and its complications are&nbsp;<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK430749/" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">most likelyTrusted Source</a>&nbsp;to affect:</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:list -->
<ul><li>adults older than age 65</li><li>people with existing health conditions</li><li>people with a weakened immune system</li><li>people who smoke</li><li>people who are malnourished</li></ul>
<!-- /wp:list -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>Children younger than 5 years also have a&nbsp;<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC7458534/" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">higher riskTrusted Source</a>&nbsp;of CAP, as well as those who may interact with them in day care settings.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:heading {"level":3} -->
<h3>Health conditions</h3>
<!-- /wp:heading -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>Certain conditions may increase your risk of developing CAP. According to a&nbsp;<a href="https://www.karger.com/Article/Fulltext/479089" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">2017 review</a>&nbsp;of 29 studies, these include:</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:list -->
<ul><li><a href="https://www.healthline.com/health/copd/understanding-chronic-bronchitis">chronic bronchitis</a>&nbsp;or&nbsp;<a href="https://www.healthline.com/health/copd/copd-and-pneumonia-understanding-your-risk">COPD</a></li><li><a href="https://www.healthline.com/health/asthma/asthma-and-pneumonia">asthma</a></li><li>diseases of the mouth, teeth, or gums</li><li>conditions that cause impaired function</li></ul>
<!-- /wp:list -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>While the review was inconclusive on whether heart disease was a risk factor, other&nbsp;<a href="https://thorax.bmj.com/content/70/10/984" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">research from 2015</a>&nbsp;suggests it is.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>Other conditions, such as&nbsp;<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC4879333/" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">diabetesTrusted Source</a>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC6280505/" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">liver diseaseTrusted Source</a>, may affect your outlook with CAP.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>Researchers in the 2017 review also identified certain medications that may increase your risk:</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:list -->
<ul><li><a href="https://www.healthline.com/health/immunosuppressant-drugs">immunosuppressants</a></li><li>oral steroids</li><li><a href="https://www.healthline.com/health/gerd/proton-pump-inhibitors">proton pump inhibitors</a>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<a href="https://www.healthline.com/health/gerd/h2-blockers">H2 blockers</a>&nbsp;(both used to treat gastric reflux)</li></ul>
<!-- /wp:list -->

<!-- wp:heading {"level":3} -->
<h3>Environmental exposure</h3>
<!-- /wp:heading -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>According to the&nbsp;<a href="https://www.who.int/news-room/fact-sheets/detail/pneumonia" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">World Health OrganizationTrusted Source</a>, environmental factors may also affect your risk of CAP. These include:</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:list -->
<ul><li>indoor air pollution from biomass fuels</li><li>crowded homes</li><li>secondhand smoke</li><li><a href="https://pneumonia.biomedcentral.com/articles/10.1186/s41479-022-00094-1" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">living on or near a farm with livestockTrusted Source</a></li><li><a href="https://journals.lww.com/environepidem/Fulltext/2018/06000/High_density_poultry_operations_and.5.aspx" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">living near centers of industrial food animal production</a></li></ul>
<!-- /wp:list -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>According to&nbsp;<a href="https://thorax.bmj.com/content/70/10/984" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">2015 research</a>, people who smoke cigarettes also have a higher risk of CAP.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:heading {"level":3} -->
<h3>Zoonotic (animal) exposure</h3>
<!-- /wp:heading -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>Exposure to certain animals that may carry the germs that cause CAP could put you at risk. According to research from&nbsp;<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC7165864/" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">2016Trusted Source</a>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC7149822/" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">2017Trusted Source</a>, examples include:</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:list -->
<ul><li>birds, including poultry</li><li>rabbits</li><li>goats</li><li>sheep</li><li>pigs</li><li>cattle</li><li>sick dogs</li><li>cats in labor</li></ul>
<!-- /wp:list -->

<!-- wp:heading {"level":3} -->
<h3>Travel exposure</h3>
<!-- /wp:heading -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>The germs that cause CAP exist everywhere in the world. But some regions are more likely to have certain germs.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p><a href="https://pneumonia.biomedcentral.com/articles/10.1186/s41479-017-0026-1" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">ExpertsTrusted Source</a>&nbsp;know that travel to large gatherings abroad contributes to the spread of germs that cause CAP. Traveling, spending time on a cruise ship, or staying in a hotel can increase your risk of exposure to these germs.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>If you have symptoms of pneumonia, be sure to tell a doctor of any recent travel. It may help them make a diagnosis.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:heading -->
<h2><a>What are the symptoms of community-acquired pneumonia?</a></h2>
<!-- /wp:heading -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>Pneumonia is a serious, sometimes fatal disease. The&nbsp;<a href="https://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/10.1111/acem.13965" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">main symptoms of CAPTrusted Source</a>&nbsp;include:</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:list -->
<ul><li>cough</li><li>production of&nbsp;<a href="https://www.healthline.com/health/green-phlegm">sputum</a></li><li>fever</li><li>difficulty breathing</li><li>headache</li><li>chest pain</li><li>muscle aches</li><li>irritability and restlessness (in infants)</li><li>confusion (in older adults)</li></ul>
<!-- /wp:list -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>In some people, breathing issues and&nbsp;<a href="https://www.healthline.com/health/pulmonary-edema">fluid buildup in the lungs</a>&nbsp;may become severe. This may lead to respiratory failure and the need for&nbsp;<a href="https://www.healthline.com/health/oxygen-therapy">oxygen therapy</a>&nbsp;or mechanical ventilation.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:heading -->
<h2><a>How do doctors diagnose community-acquired pneumonia?</a></h2>
<!-- /wp:heading -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>If a doctor notices you have symptoms of CAP, they will likely perform or order the following:</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:list -->
<ul><li><strong>Medical history:</strong>&nbsp;A doctor will ask about your medical history to better understand how you may have become ill.</li><li><strong>Physical exam:</strong>&nbsp;A doctor will perform a physical exam to check for fever and lung sounds consistent with pneumonia.</li><li><strong>Chest X-ray:</strong>&nbsp;A&nbsp;<a href="https://www.healthline.com/health/chest-x-ray">chest X-ray</a>&nbsp;can show any fluid buildup or inflammation in the lungs.</li><li><strong>CT scan:</strong>&nbsp;A doctor might use a&nbsp;<a href="https://www.healthline.com/health/ct-scan">CT scan</a>&nbsp;to confirm a diagnosis or rule out other conditions. CT scans&nbsp;<a href="https://ejrnm.springeropen.com/articles/10.1186/s43055-021-00541-x" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">may be more effective</a>&nbsp;at detecting pneumonia than chest X-rays, but they are more expensive and take longer.</li><li><strong>Complete blood count (CBC):</strong>&nbsp;A&nbsp;<a href="https://www.healthline.com/health/cbc">CBC</a>&nbsp;can help doctors see whether your immune system is fighting the infection.</li><li><strong>Electrolyte panel:</strong>&nbsp;An&nbsp;<a href="https://www.healthline.com/health/basic-metabolic-panel">electrolyte panel</a>&nbsp;can check your electrolyte levels as well as your kidney and liver function.</li><li><strong>Blood, sputum, or urine tests:</strong>&nbsp;<a href="https://www.healthline.com/health/blood-culture">Blood</a>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<a href="https://www.healthline.com/health/routine-sputum-culture">sputum cultures</a>, as well as&nbsp;<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC8717893/" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">urine antigen testsTrusted Source</a>, may identify the exact cause of the infection, influencing treatment.</li><li><strong>Molecular testing:</strong>&nbsp;This is the&nbsp;<a href="https://academic.oup.com/cid/article/71/10/2744/5830781" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">standard</a>&nbsp;way to test for viral pneumonia, such as cases caused by COVID-19.&nbsp;<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC7132381/" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">Research from 2020Trusted Source</a>&nbsp;has also shown that molecular tests, like polymerase chain reaction (PCR) tests, may also be better than cultures at detecting bacterial pneumonia.</li></ul>
<!-- /wp:list -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>A doctor will also consider other potential diagnoses. Some illnesses with symptoms similar to CAP include:</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:list -->
<ul><li><a href="https://www.healthline.com/health/bronchitis">acute bronchitis</a>&nbsp;or&nbsp;<a href="https://www.healthline.com/health/acute-respiratory-disease">other respiratory infection</a></li><li><a href="https://www.healthline.com/health/copd">chronic obstructive pulmonary disease (COPD)</a></li><li><a href="https://www.healthline.com/health/heart-failure">heart failure</a>&nbsp;or&nbsp;<a href="https://www.healthline.com/health/heart-attack">heart attack</a></li><li><a href="https://www.healthline.com/health/pulmonary-embolus">pulmonary embolism</a>&nbsp;(blood clot in your lung)</li><li><a href="https://www.healthline.com/health/tuberculosis">tuberculosis</a></li></ul>
<!-- /wp:list -->

<!-- wp:heading -->
<h2><a>What is the treatment for community-acquired pneumonia?</a></h2>
<!-- /wp:heading -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>If you have CAP, your treatment plan will depend on your symptoms and the specific cause of your infection. A doctor will also consider how severe your symptoms are.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>According to 2017 research,&nbsp;<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC7149822/" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">80%Trusted Source</a>&nbsp;of people in the United States can treat CAP at home. If your doctor determines you have a milder case of CAP from&nbsp;<a href="https://www.healthline.com/health/bacterial-pneumonia">bacteria</a>, they may prescribe&nbsp;<a href="https://www.healthline.com/health/how-do-antibiotics-work">antibiotics</a>&nbsp;for you to take at home. A doctor will likely prescribe&nbsp;<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK430749/" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">one of the followingTrusted Source</a>:</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:list -->
<ul><li><a href="https://www.healthline.com/health/amoxicillin-oral-tablet">amoxicillin</a></li><li><a href="https://www.healthline.com/health/drugs/azithromycin-cost">azithromycin</a></li><li><a href="https://www.healthline.com/health/drugs/clarithromycin-oral-tablet">clarithromycin</a></li><li><a href="https://www.healthline.com/health/drugs/doxycycline-cost">doxycycline</a></li></ul>
<!-- /wp:list -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>It’s important to take antibiotics as prescribed. If you don’t follow the proper regimen, the bacteria could become&nbsp;<a href="https://www.healthline.com/health/antibiotics/how-do-bacteria-become-resistant-to-antibiotics">antibiotic resistant</a>.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>If you have a more severe case of CAP, you may need to get treatment in a hospital. Healthcare professionals can provide a variety of intravenous (IV) antibiotic treatments based on your specific situation at a hospital.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>But antibiotics do not work for cases of&nbsp;<a href="https://www.healthline.com/health/viral-pneumonia">viral pneumonia</a>. You may need to let the virus run its course. In some cases, you may be able to use antiviral medication. Examples include:</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:list -->
<ul><li>remdesivir (Veklury) for&nbsp;<a href="https://www.healthline.com/health/coronavirus-treatment">COVID-19</a></li><li>oseltamivir (Tamiflu) for&nbsp;<a href="https://www.healthline.com/health/flu-treatments">influenza</a></li><li>inhaled ribavirin for&nbsp;<a href="https://www.healthline.com/health/respiratory-syncytial-virus-rsv">respiratory syncytial virus (RSV)</a></li></ul>
<!-- /wp:list -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>There are other actions you can take to&nbsp;<a href="https://www.nhs.uk/conditions/pneumonia/treatment/" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">manage symptoms</a>&nbsp;of viral CAP:</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:list -->
<ul><li>Take over-the-counter pain relievers, like&nbsp;<a href="https://www.healthline.com/health/pain-relief/ibuprofen-vs-acetaminophen">acetaminophen or ibuprofen</a>, to reduce fever.</li><li>Drink plenty of fluids to stay hydrated.</li><li>Get enough rest to allow your body to recover.</li><li><a href="https://www.healthline.com/health/quit-smoking">Quit smoking</a>&nbsp;if you regularly smoke.</li></ul>
<!-- /wp:list -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>If your symptoms are severe, you may need to go to the hospital. Additional treatments in the hospital may include:</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:list -->
<ul><li>oxygen therapy</li><li><a href="https://www.healthline.com/health/intravenous-fluid-regulation">intravenous (IV) fluids</a></li><li>respiratory support with a ventilator</li></ul>
<!-- /wp:list -->

<!-- wp:heading -->
<h2><a>What are the potential complications of community-acquired pneumonia?</a></h2>
<!-- /wp:heading -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>With CAP comes the risk of possible complications. These are more likely if doctors don’t make a timely diagnosis or if initial treatments don’t work.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p><a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC7162259/" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">Possible complicationsTrusted Source</a>&nbsp;include:</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:list -->
<ul><li><strong>Pleural effusion:</strong>&nbsp;<a href="https://www.healthline.com/health/pleural-effusion">Pleural effusion</a>&nbsp;is the buildup of fluid in your pleura, the space between your lungs and chest wall.</li><li><strong>Empyema:</strong>&nbsp;<a href="https://www.healthline.com/health/empyema">Empyema</a>&nbsp;is the buildup of pus in the pleural space.</li><li><strong>Lung abscesses:</strong>&nbsp;An&nbsp;<a href="https://www.healthline.com/health/lung-abscess">abscess</a>&nbsp;is a pus-filled cavity that, in this case, forms in your lung.</li><li><strong>Sepsis:</strong>&nbsp;<a href="https://www.healthline.com/health/sepsis">Sepsis</a>&nbsp;is an extreme immune response to an infection.</li><li><strong>Acute respiratory distress syndrome (ARDS):</strong>&nbsp;<a href="https://www.healthline.com/health/acute-respiratory-failure">ARDS</a>&nbsp;occurs when the lungs become severely inflamed and fill with fluid, preventing oxygen from getting into the blood.</li></ul>
<!-- /wp:list -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>Complications like sepsis and ARDS can cause organ failure and death.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:heading -->
<h2><a>What is the outlook for people with community-acquired pneumonia?</a></h2>
<!-- /wp:heading -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>With rapid and appropriate treatment, many people fully recover from CAP without complications. Young people tend to recover fully more quickly.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>If CAP is due to bacteria, you may start to feel better&nbsp;<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK430749/" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">within 5 to 7 daysTrusted Source</a>&nbsp;of starting antibiotics. Still, it can take&nbsp;<a href="https://www.nhs.uk/conditions/pneumonia/treatment/" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">months</a>&nbsp;for all your symptoms to resolve.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>If you have a mild case of CAP, full recovery is possible with rest, antibiotics or antivirals, and sleep.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>More severe cases of CAP may require lengthy hospital stays to help keep you stable and aid recovery. For people admitted to intensive care, the death rate can be as high as&nbsp;<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK430749/" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">23%Trusted Source</a>, according to 2021 research.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:heading -->
<h2><a>How can I prevent community-acquired pneumonia?</a></h2>
<!-- /wp:heading -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>Taking precautions against illness, such as getting an annual flu shot, can reduce your risk of CAP. The&nbsp;<a href="https://www.cdc.gov/flu/prevent/qa_fluzone.htm" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC)Trusted Source</a>&nbsp;recommends that people ages 65 and older get a&nbsp;<a href="https://www.healthline.com/health/flu/flu-shots-seniors-types-cost">high dose flu vaccine</a>.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>People over 65 can also consider getting the&nbsp;<a href="https://www.healthline.com/health/how-long-does-a-pneumonia-shot-last">pneumococcal vaccine</a>&nbsp;to prevent CAP. This is especially important if you have other health conditions or if you smoke.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>You may need a booster shot if you received your vaccine before age 65, or if you have a weakened immune system.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>Other everyday actions you can do to help prevent disease include the following:</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:list -->
<ul><li><a href="https://www.healthline.com/health/washing-hands">Wash your hands</a>&nbsp;frequently, especially after using the bathroom or being in public.</li><li>Cough into your elbow when you need to cough.</li><li>Keep a physical distance from people who are ill.</li><li>If you smoke or vape, consider quitting to reduce damage to your lungs. Such damage can make you more vulnerable to pneumonia infection.</li></ul>
<!-- /wp:list -->

<!-- wp:heading -->
<h2><a>Takeaway</a></h2>
<!-- /wp:heading -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>Community-acquired pneumonia (CAP) is the most common type of pneumonia. The term refers to pneumonia that you contract outside of a hospital setting.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>While many people recover from CAP with rest and antibiotic or antiviral treatment, it can be especially serious for older adults and people with existing health conditions.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>Potential complications of CAP can be life threatening. But people in high risk groups can take precautions against severe disease, such as getting an annual flu shot.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

